What libraries are and why we need to import them: Libraries are pre-written code that extends the functionality of Python. They provide functions that can be used without having to write the code from scratch. We need to import these libraries because Python does not have these functions built-in. Python libraries are good for data science, data visualization, machine learning, math, and more.

What each Library Does:

Pandas - This is a data manipulation and analysis library. With this library, you can manipulate numerical tables and time series data using the operations and data structures it offers. In this project, I have used Pandas primarily for converting my data into Dataframes instead of lists, so that the outputted information is easier to read. I also used functionality from the Pandas library to read in the intial datafile.

Numpy - This library deals with matrices and large multi-dimensional arrays as well as other numerical operations. In this project specifically, an example of how I used functionality from the Numpy library was to use the .dtype attribute to get the datatype of the elements that were stored in numpy arrays.

Matplotlib - This library allows for creating 2D charts and other visualizations. It can also be used to create interactive figures. In this project, I used matplotlib to create the visuals for stacked bar charts in Task 5.

Seaborn - This library is based on Matplotlib and is also used to create charts with an emphasis on statistical graphics. It is a popular library for data exploration. In this project, I used seaborn to plot histograms and bar charts to explore the columns in the dataset in more depth. I also used this library to create a pairplot and a heatmap to explore correlations between columns and the target variable.

Math - This library is used to provide more complex mathematical functions that can be used in the code. For example, this library provides trigonomic functions, exponential and logarithmic functions, constants, and ceiling and floor functions. I used this library to use the log function in a calculation to find a good bin size for the histograms (see Task 3 for more details).

Sklearn - This library is a machine learning library that was built on SciPy, Numpy, and Matplotlib. It is useful for regression, classification, clustering, dimensionality reduction, model selection, and preprocessing. In this project, this is the library I used to help build the models in Task 7. In the library import up above I imported DecisionTreeClassifier, SVC, MLP, and KNN for the models as well as metrics to evaluate the models. This library also allowed me to import the GridsearchCV, which was used to find the best models.

The average age of those in this dataset is 38 years with 90 years being the max and 17 years of age being the minimum. Thus, there is a wide age range for this dataset. According to the census metafile in the project description, fnlwgt represents final weight, which is "controlled to independent estimates of the civilian noninstitutional population of the US." Task 2: Column by Column Exploration¶

Create Counting Function¶

In [12]:
def counting_values(dataframe, column_name):
  values = dataframe[column_name].value_counts()
  return values

This function will count each kind of value in each column to help determine which value in each column is the most or least prevelant.

Function to Calculate Optimal Bin Size for Histograms Based on Sturges Rule¶

In [13]:
def calculate_bin_size(n):
    result = 1 + 3.3 * math.log(n)
    return result
In [14]:
n_value = 32561
In [15]:
result = calculate_bin_size(n_value)
print(result)

35.28987275617938

This function was created to determine the optimal bin size using Sturges Rule for the histograms that will be created below for continous variables. According to https://themanufacturingacademy.com/sturges-rule-a-method-for-selecting-the-number-of-bins-in-a-histogram/, Sturges rule is meant to optimize bin size by ensuring bin size in not too large, which could make the data look discontinous, or too small, which could "over smooth" the data. The n_value above represents the number of samples (or rows) in the dataset.

Task 3: Target Variable Exploration¶

1. Classification or Regression Task?¶

This data mining task is a classification task. A classification task is a supervised machine learning task, meaning it includes a target variable, labeled inputs, and outputs. The goal of a classification task is to assign an input instance into a predefined class. In this project, the goal is to predict if a certain instance is labeled <=50K or >50K based on the similarities the model finds in that instance as compared to others. The output of a classification model will be categorical.

On the other hand, while regression tasks are also supervised ML tasks, they are attempting to predict a continuous numerical value or quantity. For example, regression models may be used to predict a stock price or a product's cost.

2. Is the Target Variable Balanced or Imbalanced?¶

In [78]:
nc_values = counting_values(p1_data, 'y')
print(nc_values)

 <=50K    24720
 >50K      7841
Name: y, dtype: int64
In [79]:
p1_data.y.value_counts(normalize=True)
Out[79]:
 <=50K    0.75919
 >50K     0.24081
Name: y, dtype: float64

The target variable is imbalanced as most of the rows have a y variable of <=50K (75.91%). This is significant because bias could occur in model training as the model may not be able to predict instances from the minority class since it focuses mostly on the majority class. Furthermore, the accuracy metric may be misleading because the model will have a high accuracy as it will likely predict the majority class. While most of the data falls into the majority class there are still 7,841 instances that could be misclassified. When it is important to correctly classify the minority class, the accuracy metric would not be good to rely on alone in the case of an imbalanced y variable. Because of this imbalance, the model may struggle to generalize well to new data.

3. What a Majority Classifier's Accuracy Would be on This Target Variable¶

In [82]:
ax = sns.countplot(x=p1_data["y"])
ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right")
Out[82]:
[Text(0, 0, ' <=50K'), Text(1, 0, ' >50K')]

The majority class is the <=50K class in this scenario because it has the most number of instances. Since the majority classifier would always predict the majority class we can find the accuracy by taking the number of all of the instances that belong to the majority class (24,720) and dividing it by the total number of instances. Thus, 24,720 / (24,720 + 7,841) yields 75.9% as seen in the normalized value counts code above. Therefore, any model developed in the Model Building section must have a higher accuracy than 75.9% to outperform the majority classifier.

4. Ranked Classification Performance Metrics to be Used¶

Based on the imbalanced target variable, I will be using precision and f1 score metrics in addition to the accuracy metric to better determine model performance. As stated previously, the accuracy metric may not be as useful when looking at just this metric alone due to the imbalanced target variable. Therefore, precision and f1 score will provide a better picture of model performance. I would rank the metrics in order of importance as follows with 1 being the highest and 3 being the lowest:

1) F1 Score: is a blend of precision and recall; therefore, it is a blend of how well the model can consider both false positives and false negatives. An F1 Score is calculated as follows: (2 Precision Recall ) / (Precision + Recall). I ranked this metric as number one because, in this case, there is not much context behind why we are classifying the variables as either two of these classes; therefore, we don't know if it would be more important for the model to more accurately classify one class over the other. Thus, F1 Score will show how the model is performing more overall.

2) Precision is an assessment of how well a model can avoid false positives. It is measuring how many true positives there were to the total number of positives ( i.e. TP / (TP + FP) ). I ranked this metric in second place of importance because it is showing specifically how well the model can correctly classify the positive class. The higher this metric is, the lower the amount of instances that are being falsely classified as <=50K when they are really >50K.

3) Accuracy: is the overall correctness of the model and is calculated by taking the sum of all correct classifications and dividing by the total number of instances ( i.e. (TP + TN) / Total ). Including this metric was important so I could compare all the model's accuracies to the majority classifier's (baseline) accuracy. However, this metric is still in third place because, alone, it does not provide as good of an assessment of model performance since the target variable is imbalanced.

Decision Tree Models are used for classification or regression tasks. In this case, the decision tree is used for classifcation. These models have decision nodes where a feature will split the data into groups. The model will attempt to choose the feature that best separates the data into a distinct group.

All of the models in this dataframe have an f1 score of 0.91. f1-score in machine learning is a blend of precision and recall. The f1 score is a useful model evaluation metric in situations where there are imbalanced classes as they take into account both false positives and false negatives rather than just the amount of incorrect predictions. In this case, the dataset is relatively imbalanced as 75.9% of the data set is classified as the <=50K target variable. Thus, in this case, the f1 metric could help evaluate the model better in addition to accuracy, precision, and recall. The relatively high precision number of 0.88 indicates that the model does not make many false positive errors and the high recall number of 0.94 indicates that the model does well with capturing true positives. The model ranked number one according to f1 uses the gini criterion, has a max depth of 10, min_samples_leaf of 1 and a min_samples_split of 5. All of the best performing models used the gini criterion, had a max depth of 10 and 1 or 4 leafnodes as well as either 5 or 10 min_sample_split for the most part. All of these top 5 performing best models performed very similarly in terms of accuracy, precision, and recall. In this model we see a litle bit of drop off in performance between the mean_test_f1 and mean_train_f1 scores, but not a significant enough value to indicate that overfitting has occurred.

KNN stands for K-Nearest Neighbors. This model is used for classification or regression tasks. It does not make assumptions about the underlying data and will only make assumptions based on the similarity between the new data and the existing data points.

From the results above, we can see that a higher number of n_neighbors led to better model performance. Additionally, the two models with uniform weights had better performance. The best performing model had 9 n_neighbors and a uniform weight. However, models ranked 3 - 5 exhibited pretty signifcant overfitting. These models all experienced an 11% drop-off in the mean_f1 and mean_precision scores from the training to testing models. They also all experienced an 18% drop-off in the mean_accuracy score from the train to test models. This highlights the earlier mentioned problem of an imbalanced target variable.

Models In Summary: Models That Stood Out & Metrics Used to Evaluate Them¶

While the top result from all of the different models performed in relatively the same range, the Decision Tree and the KNN models performed the best in terms of f1-score with scores of 0.91 and 0.89, respectively. These models also had some of the highest precision metrics at 0.88 and 0.87, respectively. If comparing all the models only on an f1-score, the MLP model (rank 1) performed the worst at 0.87. However, this score is still pretty comparable to the other models.

I was using F1 score, precision, and accuracy metrics to evaluate each of these models. A strength of the F1 score is that it considers both precision and recall, providing a more wholistic overview of model performance. Additionally, it is useful for imabalanced datasets. However, a weakness of the F1 score metric is that, in the case of a model needing one class to be better predicted than another, it would not be as useful in showing false positives or false negatives individually. For example, if we discovered that the cost of false positives is high, then we would want to focus more on precision rather than the F1 score.

A srength of the precision metric is that it can help show if there is a high ratio of false positives in the dataset. A weakness is that precision doesn't consider false negatives. This could be problematic in a model with a high rate of false negatives.

A srength of the accuracy metric is that it is easily interpretable and widely adopted. This metric provides an overall measure of model performance. It is also useful for balanced data sets. A weakness of the accuracy metric is that it can be misleading for imbalanced datasets like this one. When looking at accuracy alone, it can be difficult to identify specific types of errors (e.g. too many FP or FN errors).

Task 6: Comparison To Baseline¶

Compared to the majority classifier accuracy metric of 75% identified in Task 3, all models performed above this baseline. The top Decision Tree model had an accuracy of 85% (i.e. 10% increase in performance), which was the highest accuracy out of all of the models. The top Majority Classifier Model followed in second place with an accuracy of 84% (i.e. 9% increase in performance). The top KNN model performed the third best in comparison to the baseline with an accuracy of 83% (i.e. 8% increase in performance). The top SVM and MLP Models performed the worst compared to the other models, but still above the baseline at 80% (i.e. 5% increase in performance) and 79% (i.e. 4% increase in performance), respectively. Therefore, we can say that all of the models exhibited better rates of learning patterns from the data rather than relying on simple majority voting, particularly the Decision Tree model.

Task 7: Final Model Recommendation¶

The model that performed the best was the Decision Tree Model with these parameters:

{'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 10, 'min_samples_leaf': 1, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'random_state': 42}

This model had the highest f1-score out of all the other models at 0.91. Additionally, this model is performing at slightly higher than the majority classifier model f1-score of 0.90 and is performing way above the majority classifier baseline accuracy identified in Task 3 with a 10% increase in accuracy. All other models had an f1-score below 0.90. Thus, if we were to select a model that would best predict who would belong to the classes <=50K or >50K, then I would select this decision tree model based on the high accuracy, precision, and f1-score metrics of this model.
